__data__.text: american revolution: the american revolution was an ideological and political movement in the thirteen colonies that culminated in the american revolutionary war  leading to the establishment of the united states of america

thirteen colonies: the thirteen colonies  established in the 17th century as part of the english empire  played a crucial role in the american revolution<SEP>the thirteen colonies were affected by the royal proclamation of 1763 and tensions with native americans<SEP>the thirteen colonies were the british colonies in north america that played a significant role in the american revolution
british america: british america refers to the territories in north america under british rule during the american revolution
american revolutionary war: the american revolutionary war was launched in 1775 and led to the independence of the thirteen colonies from british rule
battles of lexington and concord: the battles of lexington and concord marked the beginning of the american revolutionary war in 1775
leaders of the american revolution: leaders of the american revolution were colonial separatist leaders who advocated for independence from british rule

second continental congress: the second continental congress represented the colonies and played a key role in the american revolution  including the appointment of george washington as commander in chief
george washington: george washington was appointed as the commander in chief of the continental army during the american revolutionary war
declaration of independence: the declaration of independence was adopted in 1776  formalizing the colonies  independence from britain
siege of yorktown: the siege of yorktown in 1781 was a decisive victory for the continental army  leading to the end of the revolutionary war
king george iii: king george iii acknowledged the independence of the colonies after the siege of yorktown  leading to the treaty of paris
treaty of paris: the treaty of paris in 1783 formally recognized the independence of the united states  ending the revolutionary war
stamp act congress: the stamp act congress in 1765 protested against taxation without representation  a key grievance that fueled the revolution
boston massacre: the boston massacre in 1770 heightened tensions between the colonies and britain  leading to further resistance
boston tea party: the boston tea party in 1773 was a protest against british taxation policies  symbolizing colonial resistance
first continental congress: the first continental congress in 1774 marked the colonies  united resistance against british policies
articles of confederation: the articles of confederation were debated in the second continental congress as an early attempt at self governing rule in the colonies
thomas jefferson: thomas jefferson authored the declaration of independence  embodying key political philosophies of the revolution

france: france is the primary location involved in funding the anglo french war and facing a debt crisis<SEP>france supported the american colonies during the revolutionary war  contributing to their victory
marquis de lafayette: marquis de lafayette supported washington in the siege of yorktown  aiding in the victory over the british
charles cornwallis: charles cornwallis was a british general defeated by washington in the siege of yorktown  leading to british surrender
british parliament: british parliament imposed taxes and regulations on the colonies  leading to increased tensions and resistance
gaspee: the destruction of the royal navy customs schooner gaspee in 1772 was a significant act of rebellion against british authority
sons of liberty: the sons of liberty orchestrated events like the boston tea party to protest british policies and assert colonial rights

royal proclamation of 1763: the royal proclamation of 1763 closed off territory to white settlement  causing anger among settlers and traders<SEP>the royal proclamation of 1763 defined territorial boundaries and policies for the thirteen colonies after the french and indian war
carpenters  hall: carpenters  hall in philadelphia was the venue for the first continental congress  a pivotal event in colonial resistance
province of georgia: the province of georgia joined the first continental congress in 1775  becoming part of the united colonial resistance
patriot: patriots were individuals who supported the cause of independence and resistance against british rule during the revolution
loyalists: loyalists were individuals who remained loyal to the british crown and often faced challenges or migration after the revolution
constitutional republic: the united states became the first constitutional republic founded on principles of consent of the governed and rule of law after the revolution
capt  levi preston: capt  levi preston  a colonist from danvers  massachusetts  who expressed the sentiment of self governance and rebellion against england
danvers  massachusetts: danvers  massachusetts  a location where capt  levi preston resided and expressed his views on self governance
english empire: the english empire  to which the thirteen colonies belonged  influenced the development of american identity
british empire: the british empire  under which the thirteen colonies were governed  underwent significant changes during the colonial period
english civil war: the english civil war  a historical event that contributed to the development of a unique american identity
puritan colonies of new england: the puritan colonies of new england  which supported the commonwealth government during the english civil war
king philip s war: king philip s war  a conflict that involved the new england colonies and native american tribes  shaping american identity
stuart restoration: the stuart restoration  a historical event that influenced the recognition of charles ii as the legitimate king in massachusetts
dominion of new england: the dominion of new england  a consolidation of colonies by james ii  faced opposition from the colonists
edmund andros: edmund andros  appointed as royal governor of the dominion of new england  implemented policies that led to resentment
glorious revolution of 1688: the glorious revolution of 1688  a significant event that resulted in the removal of james ii from power
boston revolt of 1689: the boston revolt of 1689  an uprising that overthrew dominion rule in new england
william and mary: william and mary  the new monarchs after the glorious revolution  granted new charters to the new england colonies
house of lords: the house of lords  where aristocrats inherited seats in the british government
house of commons: the house of commons  where the gentry and merchants controlled the elected representatives in the british government
navigation acts: the navigation acts  a series of laws that regulated colonial trade and restricted interactions with foreign countries
molasses act 1733: the molasses act 1733  a law that imposed duties on foreign molasses and led to colonial protests

french and indian war: the french and indian war  a conflict in which the british government and the colonies cooperated militarily<SEP>the french and indian war was a significant conflict involving british soldiers  colonial volunteers  and territorial acquisitions
british government: the british government fielded soldiers and contributed to the war effort during the french and indian war  acquiring territory from france
colonies: the colonies contributed money to the war effort during the french and indian war and were involved in the conflict
great britain: great britain defeated france during the french and indian war and acquired territory east of the mississippi river
bute ministry: the bute ministry decided to garrison soldiers in north america and station a standing army to provide defense and prevent conflicts
british army officers: british army officers were allowed to remain on active duty with full pay in north america  politically well connected and involved in defense
native americans: native americans were involved in conflicts with white colonists and british soldiers in newly acquired territories
french: the french were defeated by great britain during the french and indian war  leading to territorial acquisitions
spanish: the spanish were present in florida and were a foreign population in territories acquired by great britain
white colonists: white colonists instigated conflicts with native americans and were prevented from doing so by british soldiers
customs duties: british soldiers helped collect customs duties in the newly acquired territories  contributing to revenue generation
migration: migration increased beyond the appalachian mountains after the french threat was removed  leading to conflicts
pontiac s war: native americans launched pontiac s war in response to westward migration and conflicts with white settlers
north america: north america was the location where the bute ministry decided to garrison soldiers and station a standing army
appalachian mountains: the appalachian mountains served as a boundary for westward migration and were mentioned in the royal proclamation of 1763
mississippi river: the mississippi river marked the eastern boundary of territory acquired by great britain after defeating france
grenville ministry: the grenville ministry issued the royal proclamation of 1763  affecting westward migration and relations with native americans
land speculators: land speculators were angered by the royal proclamation of 1763  impacting their interests in westward expansion
standing army: the decision to station a standing army in north america was made to provide defense and prevent conflicts in acquired territories
french revolution: the french revolution was a period of political and societal change in france  marked by significant events such as the estates general of 1789 and the coup of 18 brumaire in 1799

estates general: the estates general is summoned to address tax issues and political conflict  last meeting in 1614<SEP>the estates general of 1789 was a pivotal event in the french revolution  leading to the formation of the national assembly and subsequent revolutionary actions
coup of 18 brumaire: the coup of 18 brumaire on 9 november 1799 marked the end of the french revolution and the establishment of new political structures
ancien r gime: the ancien r gime refers to the old regime in france  characterized by social  political  and economic structures that were challenged by the revolution
louis xvi: louis xvi was the monarch during the french revolution  facing challenges and opposition that ultimately led to his execution in 1793
national assembly: the national assembly was formed by the representatives of the third estate during the french revolution  asserting their authority and initiating revolutionary measures
storming of the bastille: the storming of the bastille on 14 july was a symbolic event in the french revolution  representing the people s defiance against the monarchy and feudal system
reign of terror: the reign of terror was a period of radical actions and executions during the french revolution  led by the committee of public safety and ending with the thermidorian reaction

__data__.text: crisis of the ancien r gime: the crisis of the ancien r gime refers to the social  economic  and political challenges faced by the pre revolutionary french state
financial crisis: the financial crisis in france during the late 18th century contributed to the conditions that led to the french revolution
committee of public safety: the committee of public safety was a governing body during the french revolution responsible for radical measures and the reign of terror
thermidorian reaction: the thermidorian reaction marked the end of the reign of terror and a shift towards more moderate governance in post revolutionary france
directory: the directory was a governing body in post revolutionary france following the reign of terror and the fall of the committee of public safety
consulate: the consulate was established after the coup of 18 brumaire  with napoleon bonaparte as first consul  marking a new phase in french governance
tax farmers: tax farmers are contracted to collect taxes  keeping a portion as personal profit
nobility: nobility benefits from exemptions  leading to a heavier tax burden on peasants
church: the church benefits from exemptions  contributing to the tax burden falling on peasants
peasants: peasants bear the main tax burden due to exemptions benefiting the nobility and church
anglo french war of 1778 1783: the anglo french war of 1778 1783 was funded by france through loans  leading to financial strain post war
monarchy: the monarchy borrows heavily post war  resulting in a debt crisis and high debt servicing requirements
calonne: calonne proposes tax reforms and faces rejection  leading to a debt crisis and political conflict
brienne: brienne faces rejection of tax proposals  leading to political crisis and the announcement of summoning an estates general
parlements: parlements block new tax laws  leading to political crisis and conflict with the crown
jacques necker: jacques necker replaces brienne  leading to the announcement of summoning an estates general
society of thirty: the society of thirty campaigns for third estate representation and individual voting rights  sparking public debate
abb  siey s: abb  siey s issues influential pamphlets advocating for third estate representation and the formation of a national assembly
jean joseph mounier: jean joseph mounier organises regional meetings and petitions in support of third estate demands
antoine barnave: antoine barnave supports third estate demands through activism and literature
maximilien robespierre: maximilien robespierre supports third estate demands through activism and regional organisation
taxes: taxes are collected but not proportionally reflected in economic growth  leading to financial challenges and social disparities
debt crisis: the debt crisis arises from heavy borrowing post war  requiring a significant portion of state revenue for debt servicing
assembly of notables: the assembly of notables rejects new taxes  advocating for approval by the estates general
public opinion: public opinion supports the parlements  leading to political unrest and riots in various towns
regional judicial bodies: regional judicial bodies are required to register new tax laws  posing challenges to reform efforts
political crisis: the political crisis emerges from conflicts between the crown and parlements  leading to public statements and unrest
censorship: censorship relaxes  allowing for increased political discourse and the publication of numerous pamphlets
political clubs: political clubs see laws relaxed against them  leading to increased activism and public engagement
